{
  "doc_id": "26053",
  "text": "Our data suggest that alternative activation at the injury site of the sciatic nerve may be a neuroprotective mechanism underlying prior exercise early after CCI, but not on day 14. Macrophage infiltration into the sciatic nerve was generally elevated after CCI, and decreased by prior voluntary wheel running, although infiltration and/or activation was pronounced on day 14 relative to day 3, in contrast to previous reports. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] Notably, on day 3, immunoreactivity of Arg-1 was nonsignificantly elevated, whereas iNOS was decreased at the injury site by voluntary wheel running. This was accompanied by attenuated serum levels of proinflammatory chemokines, but elevation of the antiinflammatory cytokine IL-10 on day. Arg-1 immunoreactivity was attenuated by voluntary wheel running in the proximal and distal regions on day 3, and all regions on day 14. The general suppression of immune signaling by prior voluntary wheel running on day 14 was paralleled in the ex vivo PBMC assay, in which production of all cytokines, including IL-10, was suppressed at this time point as well. Furthermore, IL-10 was not produced by unstimulated PBMCs after voluntary wheel running. The possibility that voluntary wheel running may have induced macrophage anergy might explain the profound suppression of allodynia after injury by voluntary wheel running, although markers for macrophage infiltration and/or activation were still significantly elevated in this group relative to sham controls. Because leukocyte function and polarization shifts temporally and anatomically in response to CCI and voluntary wheel running, further characterization is required to identify the contribution of these cells to the attenuation of neuropathic pain.",
